04200nam a22006735i 9780226457949DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016054300  a9780226457949  a(DE-B1597)524285  a(OCoLC)979417251  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPS151b.N45 2017 4aPS151b.N45 2017eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a810.9/9287223  aEC 18742rvk0(DE-625)rvk/20440:1 aNelson, Deborah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTough Enough :bArbus, Arendt, Didion, McCarthy, Sontag, Weil /cDeborah Nelson. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b7 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Tough Enough -- t1. Simone Weil: Thinking Tragically in the Age of Trauma -- t2. Hannah Arendt: Irony and Atrocity -- t3. Mary McCarthy: The Aesthetic of the Fact -- t4. Susan Sontag: An-aesthetics and Agency -- t5. Diane Arbus: A Feeling for the Camera -- t6. Joan Didion: The Question of Self-Pity -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book focuses on six brilliant women who are often seen as particularly tough-minded: Simone Weil, Hannah Arendt, Mary McCarthy, Susan Sontag, Diane Arbus, and Joan Didion. Aligned with no single tradition, they escape straightforward categories. Yet their work evinces an affinity of style and philosophical viewpoint that derives from a shared attitude toward suffering. What Mary McCarthy called a “cold eye” was not merely a personal aversion to displays of emotion: it was an unsentimental mode of attention that dictated both ethical positions and aesthetic approaches. Tough Enough traces the careers of these women and their challenges to the pre-eminence of empathy as the ethical posture from which to examine pain. Their writing and art reveal an adamant belief that the hurts of the world must be treated concretely, directly, and realistically, without recourse to either melodrama or callousness. As Deborah Nelson shows, this stance offers an important counter-tradition to the familiar postwar poles of emotional expressivity on the one hand and cool irony on the other. Ultimately, in its insistence on facing reality without consolation or compensation, this austere “school of the unsentimental” offers new ways to approach suffering in both its spectacular forms and all of its ordinariness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAestheticsxPsychological aspects. 0aSuffering in art. 0aSuffering in literature. 0aToughness (Personality trait) 0aToughness (Personality trait). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aDiane Arbus.  aHannah Arendt.  aJoan Didion.  aMary McCarthy.  aSimone Weil.  aSusan Sontag.  aaesthetics.  aemotion.  astyle.  aunsentimental.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226457949423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226457949/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles